                            <body>
                                <p> By Stella Mapenzauswa</p>
                                <p> HARARE, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Zimbabwe launched a blistering  attack on Australian Prime Minister John Howard on Monday,  accusing him of racism and treating Africans in the same way  Australia treats its Aborigines.</p>
                                <p> Government ministers defended President Robert Mugabe's snub  of a special Commonwealth meeting in Nigeria on Monday where the  leaders of Australia, Nigeria and South Africa were expected to  weigh tougher sanctions against Zimbabwe.</p>
                                <p> "No serious person expected us to be part of that kind of a  circus," Information Minister Jonathan Moyo was quoted as saying  in the state-owned Herald newspaper.</p>
                                <p> "The whole thing stinks of an orchestrated media event  designed to insult the president and demonise Zimbabwe at the  behest of Britain with Australia playing the role of a  cheerleader," he said.</p>
                                <p> "John Howard should disabuse himself of the folly that he  can treat Africans the same way he treats Aborigines," Moyo said  in a belligerent tone normally reserved for Zimbabwe's former  colonial ruler Britain.</p>
                                <p> Nigeria, which is hosting the talks, said on Sunday that  Mugabe had decided at the last minute to boycott the meeting,  complaining of being made to feel "he was going to be  court-martialled in Abuja".</p>
                                <p> Diplomats in Abuja said Mugabe was angered by the suggestion  in his invitation letter, sent by committee chairman Howard,  that Zimbabwe's domestic politics would be on the agenda.</p>
                                <p> "He said he would only come if Howard agreed that the  problems of Australian Aboriginals be discussed at the meeting,"  a Nigerian official told Reuters.</p>
                                <p> Australia's 400,000 Aborigines want a formal apology from  the government for past injustices, including the forced removal  of tens of thousands of mixed race children from their families.</p>
                                <p> </p>
                                <p> "CRUDE AND RUDE"</p>
                                <p> The Herald quoted a Zimbabwean official as saying Mugabe's  unsigned invitation letter from Howard was "arrogant, racist,  undiplomatic, crude and rude".</p>
                                <p> The troika has the Commonwealth's mandate to recommend  sanctions and suspension, and could make such a move in six  months when the current limited measures against Zimbabwe run  their full course.</p>
                                <p> The Commonwealth, which groups 54 mostly former British  colonies, slapped "symbolic" sanctions on Zimbabwe in March  following the hotly disputed re-election of Mugabe, in power in  the Southern African country since 1980.</p>
                                <p> Commonwealth observers and a group of southern African  parliamentarians said the vote was flawed, but observers from  South Africa, Namibia and Nigeria said the poll was legitimate.</p>
                                <p> Zimbabwe's main opposition, the Movement for Democratic  Change (MDC), has called for sterner action against Mugabe for  refusing to call fresh elections and failing to end political  violence against his opponents.</p>
                                <p> The government has insisted the election was free and fair,  and rejected allegations of state-sponsored violence.  </p>
